Yes, I do.

Y'all have never worked in a professional kitchen, have you? Although water-baths, bain-maries (bains-marie?), and double-boilers all use hot water to gentle the heating process--pace Wikipedia, and Amazon--there are some differences.

A water-bath is used in an oven, to temper the heat, but also to provide humidity in the oven, so the flan or cheesecake or whatever doesn't dry out. A bain-marie and a double boiler are more similar, except one wouldn't normally *cook*  on a bain-marie, except in unusual situations. It's generally reserved for reheating food, or keeping it warm. Unless the bain-marie is turned too high, in which case your hotel pan of baked ziti might get all over-cooked and dried out on the bottom. Btw, I looked up the "flan double-boilers" on Amazon--what a total gimmicky waste of money and kitchen counter space!

And let's not even bring up sous-vide!

It is interesting to think that bain-maries had their origins as alchemical equipment.

